Back in 2010 Gary Nafis was notified of this population and sent me to survey it. During the survey I was able to not only determine how far the population had spread, but discovered its origins and date of introduction, which was later confirmed by Guntram Deichsel via genetic data. Guntram Deichsel, Gary, and myself published a note in Herp Review. Details are given in Deichsel, G., G. Nafis & J. Hakim (2010): Podarcis siculus (siculus) â€“ U.S.A, California, Los Angeles. Herpetological Review, 41 (4): 513-514. More pictures are presented at www.californiaherps.com.

As of 2018 the population was continuing to grow and spread. It is only anecdotal, but I did not encounter fence lizards or alligator lizards within the populated area, though both were found just outside of it. However, invasive Moorish Wall Geckos were found within the populated area.

description:
sagebrush pygmyleaf, Loeflingia squarrosa var. artemisiarum, Nevada, Prison Hill, Carson Valley drainage, elevation 1486 m (4875 ft).

This rare (or at least rarely noticed) plant inhabits loose sandy desert soils of the interior basin and range of the western United States, and only germinates in the wettest years. Among the humblest of desert plants, this species has no petals, and the rest of its flower parts are tiny and look very much like the leaves, making it hard to tell that this plant is in full flower and fruit.

description:
During a creek survey I found this FHYL. This remains the only adult FHYL frog I have found in the 5 mile recreation area of Bidwell Park. 
Upstream of this portion of Big Chico Creek is an ecological reserve where the population of FHYL frogs is strong. The difference is at the reserve the population of bullfrogs is managed. In Bidwell Park, it is not managed at all.The bullfrogs have almost completely wiped out the population of FHYL frogs.  Two different management philosophies with two very different results.
my first observation of this species

description:
desert calico, Loeseliastrum matthewsii, Owens Valley on lower slopes of Sierra Nevada, elevation 1255 m (4115 ft).  Most plants in this population showed unusual yellow flower coloration, often (as in this example) mixed with the more typical pink on the same plant, and even in the same flower.  Note that all the new buds are yellow.  And it had rained substantially the day before.

My working hypothesis: the younger, developing flowers are susceptible to differential leaching of pigments by rain water, removing the presumably more-soluble pink (anthocyanic) component(s), while those pigments have become more fixed in the older flowers.  Other ideas??

This area also appears as a connectivity point between coastal-Valley Ford area eastward to expansive grasslands, mostly agricultural, in West Petaluma.

description: Many thanks to botaness for tipping me off to the fact that these (and many other cool things) are flowering on Mt. D at the moment. I believe the fat lower lip sets this apart from the similar P. elongata. I saw the greatest concentrations along the Falls Trail, but they seemed to be scattered here and there all over. CNPS lists them as "fairly threatened" (4.2), but they seem to be doing pretty well on Mt. Diablo.

This is a werid flower. There were only two pedicels, the petals were not that hairy, the corolla was not striped, and it was growing in Lithophragma habitat (under oak / manzanita, I think), all of which suggested O. uniflora to me, so I was all excited that I might have found a yellow one. But now that I'm doing my homework, I see that O. uniflora isn't supposed to be more than 5 cm tall (this was > 10 cm) and O. fasciulata can be somewhat glabrous and one-stemmed. To top that off, Jepson mentions that O. fasciculata is occasionally "intermediate to O. uniflora , generally on Galium," and lo and behold, if you use your imagination while looking at the whole-plant shot below, I think there's some Galium growing there, so I guess I'm going with O. fasciculata. Weird. I also suspect that some of the photos listed under O. uniflora in CalPhotos have been mis-identified.

description: When we got to Jepson Prairie and Olcott Lake, we walked around, I nerded out about flowers, Tony and his dad looked around and tolerated my frequent dives to the ground, and that was about it. Luckily, we then joined Solano County Land Trust guided tour, and man, was that fortunate. Not only did the docents show us the California Tiger Salamander we had wanted so much to see, but they also had these totally unexpted tadpole shrimp! These are ancient crustaceans that hatch, eat, breed, lay eggs, and die all in the few months between winter rains and summer heat. They're closely related to the triops that some people keep as pets. On top of all that, they're federally endangered, so even if we had known they were there, it would have been illegal for us to dip net for them! The docents had permits, so they were able to collect some to show us. So awesome.
